WEBVTT

1
00:00:05.714 --> 00:00:08.132
The first time you walk out
there. it's jaw-dropping.

2
00:00:08.133 --> 00:00:09.758
♪

3
00:00:09.759 --> 00:00:13.303
It's completely
shocking and unexpected.

4
00:00:13.304 --> 00:00:15.264
Oh. it was a great day.

5
00:00:15.265 --> 00:00:16.682
♪

6
00:00:16.683 --> 00:00:17.975
Brilliant set.

7
00:00:17.976 --> 00:00:19.852
Catherine Goldschmidt:
<i>It's really badass.</i>

8
00:00:19.853 --> 00:00:21.603
Thank you very
much. Drinks on me.

9
00:00:21.604 --> 00:00:22.813
It was a storm inside.

10
00:00:22.814 --> 00:00:24.606
Oh. my God.

11
00:00:24.607 --> 00:00:27.652
It's unbelievable!

12
00:00:28.820 --> 00:00:31.823
(epic music playing)

13
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:39.074
Free Gift Cards and Tech Items with
Southwest Points: www.fairylandshop.me

14
00:00:49.007 --> 00:00:52.176
(music fades out)

15
00:00:52.177 --> 00:00:55.846
This is a very iconic
moment in George's books.

16
00:00:55.847 --> 00:00:57.306
The Battle of Burning Mill.

17
00:00:57.307 --> 00:01:00.184
<i>Two houses that were
pitted against each other.</i>

18
00:01:00.185 --> 00:01:03.729
<i>And it's the metaphor for
the history of violence</i>

19
00:01:03.730 --> 00:01:07.649
and how you get to a point
where there is no forgiveness.

20
00:01:07.650 --> 00:01:10.695
<i>And that's where we find
ourselves this season.</i>

21
00:01:11.363 --> 00:01:13.365
♪

22
00:01:16.368 --> 00:01:18.703
Matt Smith: Morning.
Morning. How we doin'?

23
00:01:19.371 --> 00:01:21.038
Geeta Vasant Patel: <i>Jim
Clay. in collaboration with</i>

24
00:01:21.039 --> 00:01:22.581
<i>the special effects department.</i>

25
00:01:22.582 --> 00:01:26.502
created a place that truly
felt real and haunted

26
00:01:26.503 --> 00:01:28.379
<i>and brought the book to life.</i>

27
00:01:28.380 --> 00:01:29.838
Jim Clay: <i>I was well
pleased when Ryan said</i>

28
00:01:29.839 --> 00:01:32.341
<i>we're going to feature
the interior of Harrenhal.</i>

29
00:01:32.342 --> 00:01:33.550
<i>so that was one of
the first things</i>

30
00:01:33.551 --> 00:01:35.344
<i>we went to work on designing.</i>

31
00:01:35.345 --> 00:01:39.014
Harrenhal. "It's a cursed castle
designed by a deranged mind."

32
00:01:39.015 --> 00:01:40.684
was the sort of brief I got.

33
00:01:41.059 --> 00:01:43.227
<i>And so. it's dilapidated.</i>

34
00:01:43.228 --> 00:01:46.730
<i>It's haunted by its
past and its present.</i>

35
00:01:46.731 --> 00:01:49.358
Smith: <i>Oh. it's huge. It
goes on and on and on.</i>

36
00:01:49.359 --> 00:01:51.568
<i>Jim Clay has just
done brilliant work.</i>

37
00:01:51.569 --> 00:01:53.696
The texture and the scale

38
00:01:53.697 --> 00:01:54.905
<i>and the vision behind</i>

39
00:01:54.906 --> 00:01:57.408
<i>a lot of his work
is really superior.</i>

40
00:01:57.409 --> 00:02:00.411
Melissa Bernstein: <i>It's a set that
I'd find myself getting lost in.</i>

41
00:02:00.412 --> 00:02:01.954
<i>You'd turn the wrong
corner and you're like.</i>

42
00:02:01.955 --> 00:02:03.706
<i>"Wait. where am I?"</i>

43
00:02:03.707 --> 00:02:06.250
Like. you could get as
disoriented as Daemon

44
00:02:06.251 --> 00:02:07.543
walking through that set.

45
00:02:07.544 --> 00:02:09.963
<i>And I think that's
really saying something.</i>

46
00:02:13.508 --> 00:02:14.758
Malcolm Roberts:
<i>It was pretty big.</i>

47
00:02:14.759 --> 00:02:16.427
<i>I mean. it filled
the whole stage.</i>

48
00:02:16.428 --> 00:02:18.303
From a structural
point of view. mainly.

49
00:02:18.304 --> 00:02:21.598
how are you gonna hide
your integral structure

50
00:02:21.599 --> 00:02:22.933
<i>if you've got a
steel frame that.</i>

51
00:02:22.934 --> 00:02:24.309
<i>obviously. you
can't see in shot.</i>

52
00:02:24.310 --> 00:02:26.228
<i>then we've gotta try
and conceal that.</i>

53
00:02:26.229 --> 00:02:28.313
<i>That's what makes it
fun. really. though.</i>

54
00:02:28.314 --> 00:02:30.441
Clay: <i>I wanted to give the
whole four-walled world</i>

55
00:02:30.442 --> 00:02:33.318
the advantages of tracking
shots. Steadicam shots.

56
00:02:33.319 --> 00:02:37.239
<i>and the actors being
enveloped in the entire world.</i>

57
00:02:37.240 --> 00:02:39.116
Dominic Masters: <i>You can go where
you like. shoot what you like.</i>

58
00:02:39.117 --> 00:02:42.244
<i>pretty much 360 around the set.</i>

59
00:02:42.245 --> 00:02:44.455
<i>Whichever way you
look. you'd be covered.</i>

60
00:02:44.456 --> 00:02:46.790
And the idea was it
should be quite a maze.

61
00:02:46.791 --> 00:02:48.459
You shouldn't feel like
you know where you are

62
00:02:48.460 --> 00:02:50.502
at any given time
in that castle.

63
00:02:50.503 --> 00:02:52.296
<i>Got lost in there most mornings.</i>

64
00:02:52.297 --> 00:02:53.797
Ryan Condal: <i>This is
honestly my favorite set</i>

65
00:02:53.798 --> 00:02:55.007
<i>that Jim has built. to date.</i>

66
00:02:55.008 --> 00:02:57.593
because it's so well
brought to life.

67
00:02:57.594 --> 00:02:59.303
the idea of this ruined castle.

68
00:02:59.304 --> 00:03:01.805
<i>the fact that he
made it rain inside.</i>

69
00:03:01.806 --> 00:03:03.432
<i>the way he made
the weirwood roots</i>

70
00:03:03.433 --> 00:03:05.768
<i>break through all of
the stones that you see.</i>

71
00:03:05.769 --> 00:03:08.812
<i>that. slowly. the castle being
reclaimed by the old gods.</i>

72
00:03:08.813 --> 00:03:10.981
This here is the guy
who makes me wet.

73
00:03:10.982 --> 00:03:12.316
- (laughter)
- Yeah.

74
00:03:12.317 --> 00:03:14.777
(indistinct chatter)

75
00:03:14.778 --> 00:03:16.528
He's the rain punisher. Tom.

76
00:03:16.529 --> 00:03:17.988
- This is it.
- Screws me up every day.

77
00:03:17.989 --> 00:03:19.865
Harrenhal. wetter than
an otter's pocket.

78
00:03:19.866 --> 00:03:23.327
- I know. But I do like a bit of rain.
- (laughter)

79
00:03:23.328 --> 00:03:25.329
Jason Rickwood: <i>Harrenhal's
supposed to be this windy. wet place</i>

80
00:03:25.330 --> 00:03:26.622
<i>and we're doing
some interior stuff</i>

81
00:03:26.623 --> 00:03:28.791
and we need it to
be raining inside

82
00:03:28.792 --> 00:03:30.334
'cause the whole idea
of it being dilapidated

83
00:03:30.335 --> 00:03:32.544
was there's holes in the
wall and holes in the roof.

84
00:03:32.545 --> 00:03:34.630
Condal: <i>Man. did
we soak that place.</i>

85
00:03:34.631 --> 00:03:36.340
<i>But it really brings
an incredible amount</i>

86
00:03:36.341 --> 00:03:37.675
of realism and
texture to the place.

87
00:03:37.676 --> 00:03:40.010
which was really important
for the storytelling.

88
00:03:40.011 --> 00:03:41.845
Mike Dawson: <i>My brief was.
"It's gonna be really damp."</i>

89
00:03:41.846 --> 00:03:43.347
<i>That was it.</i>

90
00:03:43.348 --> 00:03:45.224
<i>And in the end.
my last brief was.</i>

91
00:03:45.225 --> 00:03:47.518
"It's gotta rain inside
like it does outside."

92
00:03:47.519 --> 00:03:48.977
And it didn't stop raining.

93
00:03:48.978 --> 00:03:51.063
<i>My God. it was horrendous.</i>

94
00:03:51.064 --> 00:03:53.190
<i>But it-it looks amazing.</i>

95
00:03:53.191 --> 00:03:55.693
Masters: <i>It was a slightly
late-in-the-day idea to have the water</i>

96
00:03:55.694 --> 00:03:58.237
dripping into the set. so
we weren't totally prepared

97
00:03:58.238 --> 00:03:59.697
in terms of tanking the set.

98
00:03:59.698 --> 00:04:02.241
<i>which we normally would
if you had a lot of water.</i>

99
00:04:02.242 --> 00:04:04.493
<i>But we coped. and special
effects did a great job</i>

100
00:04:04.494 --> 00:04:06.537
with soaking up the
water around the set

101
00:04:06.538 --> 00:04:08.038
when it was all pouring in.

102
00:04:08.039 --> 00:04:10.541
Dawson: <i>It was too late
to retrospectively fix it.</i>

103
00:04:10.542 --> 00:04:12.835
<i>so we had to just
minimize damage.</i>

104
00:04:12.836 --> 00:04:14.920
So. we did individual tanks

105
00:04:14.921 --> 00:04:16.255
and tried to
contain it that way.

106
00:04:16.256 --> 00:04:18.382
<i>which worked really
well and it looked real.</i>

107
00:04:18.383 --> 00:04:19.884
♪

108
00:04:20.802 --> 00:04:22.553
<i>I thought. "Matt's gonna
freak out. ya know.</i>

109
00:04:22.554 --> 00:04:25.222
walking around in his armor
all day long with rain."

110
00:04:25.223 --> 00:04:27.725
<i>But it looked so good.
and he was lovin' it.</i>

111
00:04:27.726 --> 00:04:31.103
Smith: <i>We were wet from. like. eight
in the morning 'til eight at night.</i>

112
00:04:31.104 --> 00:04:32.855
which was quite fun.
actually. to be honest.

113
00:04:32.856 --> 00:04:35.566
<i>I love all that. Like.
gettin' sort of properly wet.</i>

114
00:04:35.567 --> 00:04:37.234
and I hate being really hot.

115
00:04:37.235 --> 00:04:39.778
but I quite like
being really wet.

116
00:04:39.779 --> 00:04:41.405
Rickwood: <i>To make sure
his continuity is correct.</i>

117
00:04:41.406 --> 00:04:42.406
<i>he's gotta be
soaked all the time.</i>

118
00:04:42.407 --> 00:04:43.699
<i>and the best way of doin' it is</i>

119
00:04:43.700 --> 00:04:44.950
<i>turn the water on and say.</i>

120
00:04:44.951 --> 00:04:46.368
<i>"Matt. can you go stand
under that. please?"</i>

121
00:04:46.369 --> 00:04:47.453
In my experience with
working with Matt.

122
00:04:47.454 --> 00:04:49.246
he likes to embrace
all the challenges

123
00:04:49.247 --> 00:04:51.415
<i>you throw at him. in that
sense. so it was good.</i>

124
00:04:51.416 --> 00:04:53.459
Goldschmidt: <i>The script is
describing the character can't see.</i>

125
00:04:53.460 --> 00:04:55.044
<i>What does that mean
for the audience?</i>

126
00:04:55.045 --> 00:04:58.088
So. that sequence wound
up being incredibly fun

127
00:04:58.089 --> 00:05:00.090
to light and conceive and shoot

128
00:05:00.091 --> 00:05:01.925
<i>because. obviously. it's
raining and lightning.</i>

129
00:05:01.926 --> 00:05:03.969
<i>and we were playing
a lot with shadows</i>

130
00:05:03.970 --> 00:05:06.055
<i>and silhouettes and film noir</i>

131
00:05:06.056 --> 00:05:10.059
but the way it looks when it's
completely wet and dripping

132
00:05:10.060 --> 00:05:13.188
<i>and he's standing there. I
mean. it's really badass.</i>

133
00:05:15.023 --> 00:05:16.649
Smith: Quite fun. though.

134
00:05:17.150 --> 00:05:19.152
♪

135
00:05:21.154 --> 00:05:22.905
Condal: <i>The Brackens
and the Blackwoods</i>

136
00:05:22.906 --> 00:05:25.574
are the Hatfields and
McCoys of this time period.

137
00:05:25.575 --> 00:05:27.618
<i>We don't really know why
they hate each other.</i>

138
00:05:27.619 --> 00:05:28.952
<i>They simply just
hate each other.</i>

139
00:05:28.953 --> 00:05:30.713
And they're always ready
to fight each other.

140
00:05:30.789 --> 00:05:32.247
That guy's gonna
rip your face off.

141
00:05:32.248 --> 00:05:34.500
- Actor: Okay. Yeah.
- Okay? Great.

142
00:05:34.501 --> 00:05:37.586
<i>Directing that opening
moment of episode 203.</i>

143
00:05:37.587 --> 00:05:41.298
where you find all the
bodies dead after a battle

144
00:05:41.299 --> 00:05:43.967
<i>took quite a bit of prep.</i>

145
00:05:43.968 --> 00:05:46.470
Aeron Bracken is
a human one minute

146
00:05:46.471 --> 00:05:48.681
and a prosthetic dummy the next.

147
00:05:48.682 --> 00:05:50.307
but you can't tell.

148
00:05:50.308 --> 00:05:52.518
Waldo Mason: <i>First thing
we did was scan his head.</i>

149
00:05:52.519 --> 00:05:54.687
- So. we gonna just lie you on the floor.
- Cool.

150
00:05:54.688 --> 00:05:56.814
And then we'll do a couple
of options of. like.

151
00:05:56.815 --> 00:05:59.983
mouth open. eyes
closed. uh. eyes open

152
00:05:59.984 --> 00:06:01.276
<i>maybe. head back.</i>

153
00:06:01.277 --> 00:06:02.861
<i>and then. we'll
run it past Geeta</i>

154
00:06:02.862 --> 00:06:03.946
<i>and she can tell
us what she likes.</i>

155
00:06:03.947 --> 00:06:05.197
<i>And we'll process whichever</i>

156
00:06:05.198 --> 00:06:06.448
version of that she likes.

157
00:06:06.449 --> 00:06:08.492
- Amazin'. Cool.
- Cool.

158
00:06:08.493 --> 00:06:09.953
And we're off.

159
00:06:10.829 --> 00:06:13.330
We've just literally
finished printing his head.

160
00:06:13.331 --> 00:06:15.541
ready to be remolded
and cleaned up.

161
00:06:15.542 --> 00:06:18.669
The shoulders in two
halves on another printer.

162
00:06:18.670 --> 00:06:21.881
Just assemble it like a. like
a jigsaw puzzle at the end.

163
00:06:23.258 --> 00:06:25.677
It's so lifelike.
It's so real.

164
00:06:26.094 --> 00:06:27.511
Rickwood: <i>It was incredible.
I mean. the fact that</i>

165
00:06:27.512 --> 00:06:29.054
<i>we were doing an
extreme close-up</i>

166
00:06:29.055 --> 00:06:30.848
on the prosthetic
dummy of an actor

167
00:06:30.849 --> 00:06:32.516
that's in the scene before.

168
00:06:32.517 --> 00:06:34.018
and you can get away with that.

169
00:06:34.019 --> 00:06:36.479
<i>just shows the quality
of Waldo's work.</i>

170
00:06:37.355 --> 00:06:38.981
So. you're lying on a
body bag. by the way.

171
00:06:38.982 --> 00:06:42.193
- Oh. great.
- Speaker: Surprise!

172
00:06:43.945 --> 00:06:46.655
Goldschmidt: <i>Geeta always imagined
it as one simple. elegant shot</i>

173
00:06:46.656 --> 00:06:48.532
<i>where we're on Aeron
Bracken's face.</i>

174
00:06:48.533 --> 00:06:51.368
<i>and you just raise up
and there's dead bodies</i>

175
00:06:51.369 --> 00:06:53.370
<i>as far as the eye can see.</i>

176
00:06:53.371 --> 00:06:56.206
<i>And on the morning when we
shot it. it had rained a lot.</i>

177
00:06:56.207 --> 00:06:59.668
And so. it was incredibly misty
and sort of spooky-looking

178
00:06:59.669 --> 00:07:02.046
and it wound up being
the perfect weather

179
00:07:02.047 --> 00:07:03.672
for a scene like that.

180
00:07:03.673 --> 00:07:05.716
Mason: <i>It's one of those ones
where you don't really know</i>

181
00:07:05.717 --> 00:07:08.719
<i>what it's gonna look like because we
knew it was gonna be in the water.</i>

182
00:07:08.720 --> 00:07:10.554
and he's kinda semi-submerged

183
00:07:10.555 --> 00:07:12.765
and the sword is going
through his neck.

184
00:07:12.766 --> 00:07:16.435
<i>which meant getting in the
stream. having to dress it in.</i>

185
00:07:16.436 --> 00:07:19.898
<i>And luckily. we had some great
props guys in waders helping us out.</i>

186
00:07:20.315 --> 00:07:24.943
The Aeron Bracken sword is
shot in extreme close-up.

187
00:07:24.944 --> 00:07:28.572
<i>and is actually one of the most
important shots in the show. for us.</i>

188
00:07:28.573 --> 00:07:32.576
<i>because it's the closest
we ever get to a sword.</i>

189
00:07:32.577 --> 00:07:35.371
There was a lot of discussion about
how we get the sword to stand up.

190
00:07:35.372 --> 00:07:37.706
<i>We ended up just driving
it so far through his neck.</i>

191
00:07:37.707 --> 00:07:39.917
<i>it would just stand
up in the ground</i>

192
00:07:39.918 --> 00:07:41.586
<i>which was fantastic for us.</i>

193
00:07:41.920 --> 00:07:43.921
Oh. that looks so
good over there.

194
00:07:43.922 --> 00:07:47.883
That (sniffles) bare back
of someone. That's great.

195
00:07:47.884 --> 00:07:50.219
Dadi Einarsson: <i>In visual
effects. the rule of thumb is</i>

196
00:07:50.220 --> 00:07:51.804
<i>you do as much
practical as you can.</i>

197
00:07:51.805 --> 00:07:53.597
With Waldo. the bar is
pretty high with him.

198
00:07:53.598 --> 00:07:57.267
so he does amazing stuff. and
we can take it from there.

199
00:07:57.268 --> 00:07:58.936
<i>There's quite a bit to
do. Uh. there's obviously</i>

200
00:07:58.937 --> 00:08:01.397
<i>a windmill that's not there
that we need to put in.</i>

201
00:08:01.398 --> 00:08:04.274
<i>Setting fire to the mill.
and boundary stones.</i>

202
00:08:04.275 --> 00:08:05.776
<i>and then we get
to that end shot.</i>

203
00:08:05.777 --> 00:08:07.277
<i>which is the aftermath
of the battle.</i>

204
00:08:07.278 --> 00:08:09.238
but we're expanding
that enormously.

205
00:08:09.239 --> 00:08:11.950
<i>So. yeah. it was a
fairly big shot for us.</i>

206
00:08:13.785 --> 00:08:15.244
Tim Lewis: <i>When
the camera tilts up</i>

207
00:08:15.245 --> 00:08:18.288
<i>and we see the aftermath
with that beautiful sword.</i>

208
00:08:18.289 --> 00:08:21.583
<i>just tells the story
without actually showing</i>

209
00:08:21.584 --> 00:08:24.586
any physical
violence whatsoever.

210
00:08:24.587 --> 00:08:26.964
Patel: <i>It was one of my
favorite days of shooting</i>

211
00:08:26.965 --> 00:08:31.135
because all departments came
together so quickly that morning

212
00:08:31.136 --> 00:08:34.805
to create the tone
of that epic moment

213
00:08:34.806 --> 00:08:36.098
in George's books.

214
00:08:36.099 --> 00:08:38.184
- No. it's good. Tight.
- (indistinct chatter)

215
00:08:38.643 --> 00:08:40.645
♪

216
00:08:42.647 --> 00:08:45.482
It's genuinely been the best
time I've ever had on set.

217
00:08:45.483 --> 00:08:47.151
Ever. It's so much fun.

218
00:08:47.152 --> 00:08:49.695
♪

219
00:08:49.696 --> 00:08:51.655
Condal: <i>Moondancer's
a brand-new dragon.</i>

220
00:08:51.656 --> 00:08:53.657
<i>so the description that
I gave to the designers</i>

221
00:08:53.658 --> 00:08:54.867
<i>was simply. "David Bowie."</i>

222
00:08:54.868 --> 00:08:56.869
And we ended up with
this like tiger-striped.

223
00:08:56.870 --> 00:08:59.830
green punk rocker with a mohawk.

224
00:08:59.831 --> 00:09:01.957
<i>and I'm thrilled with
the outcome of it.</i>

225
00:09:01.958 --> 00:09:04.710
She is the coolest of them all.

